metadata.name: Annum #694
metadata.description:
This project is being released in celebration of the 1 year aniversary of Achromat, my first release on fxhash. In addition to being inspired by Achromat, aspects of other previous projects have been incorporated. My deepest gratitude to all who have collected my work over the past year.

In live mode, add &size=<YOUR_PIXEL_SIZE> to change the pixel size of the image for export (Right click to save). For example, &size=4000 will set the width of the image to be 4000 pixels.

50% of primary sales go to Savepakistan.

metadata.name: (un)connected #147
metadata.description:
A playful collection for #fxhashturnsone.

(un)connected
the older we get,
the more we risk losing the connection,
with who we once were,
what we still are,
colorful,
loving and caring,
playful,
connected

be
childlike


Thank you very much for this amazing first year. 


Controls:

- Press [p] to save the current image
- Press [1-5] to render and save the image in a higher resolution (1 = low; 5 = high)

Made with p5. All primary sales go to Savepakistan. Royalties go to the Processing Foundation.

Tested with Safari Version 16.1 (18614.2.9.1.12) and Chrome Version 107.0.5304.87. Browser updates can affect the future behavior.

metadata.name: Capture #195
metadata.description:
The collection captures this exciting year of fast-pacing generative art and fxhash development into an abstract snapshot.

#fxhashturnsone 🥳

——————

Animation goes for 1000 frames (~16 sec).
To change the size of an image, open it in live view and add ‘&size=[size (6000 max.)]’ to the end of the URL.
Press [P] to pause.
Press [S] while paused to save the image.

Created using p5.js and GLSL.
License: CC BY-NC-SA 4.0.

——————

hrunz. — Nov. 2022.

metadata.name: Copenhagen Interpretation #97
metadata.description:
The Copenhagen Interpretation of quantum physics suggests that objects don't have physical properties until being observed.

In this generative piece by itsgalo and Spøgelsesmaskinen, a set of objects are being held in "superposition" and finally positioned when observed and minted.

Use mouse/touch to zoom, pan, and rotate. Press 's' to grab a screenshot. Best viewed in Firefox.
